Ad umbilicum adducere. “ To bring to an end.’' Among the Romans, when a book or volume was finished it was rolled around a taper stick, made ofwedar, box, ivory, or the like, and called umbilicus from its being in the middle when the work was rolled around it. The 'poets generally use the plural form of this word, in allusion to the parts which projected on either side of the book: the two extremities were called cornua.
